{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17630083","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17630083"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:12:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:12:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17305"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17305","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17305"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.05,0.2,0.2,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9995"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78750"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9995","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9995"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17305"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64098"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7220"},{"type":"tags","id":"7228"},{"type":"tags","id":"7233"},{"type":"tags","id":"7234"},{"type":"tags","id":"7418"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23410"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23412"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78750"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerves of the lumbar plexus is paired with the correct corresponding nerve roots?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lateral femoral cutaneous nerve (L2, L3)","Iliohypogastric nerve (L2)","Femoral nerve (L1, L2)","Obturator nerve (L3, L4)","Ilioinguinal nerve (L2, L3)"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral femoral cutaneous nerve\u003C/strong\u003E originates from the L2 and L3 nerve roots. It is responsible for sensory innervation to the skin of the lateral aspect of the thigh. Compression or entrapment of this nerve can lead to a condition known as meralgia paraesthetica which is characterised by numbness or tingling in the lateral thigh.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eiliohypogastric nerve\u003C/strong\u003E originates from the L1 nerve root, not L2. It provides sensory innervation to the skin over the upper buttock and lower abdomen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efemoral nerve\u003C/strong\u003E originates from the L2, L3, and L4 nerve roots, not L1 and L2. It is responsible for motor innervation to the anterior compartment of the thigh, as well as sensory innervation to the anterior thigh and the medial aspect of the leg.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eobturator nerve\u003C/strong\u003E originates from the L2, L3, and L4 nerve roots, not L3 and L4. It provides motor innervation to the medial compartment of the thigh, as well as sensory innervation to a small area of the medial thigh.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eilioinguinal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E originates from the L1 nerve root, not L2 and L3. It provides sensory innervation to the skin of the upper and medial thigh as well as parts of the external genitalia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The lateral femoral cutaneous nerve originates from the L2 and L3 nerve roots.","The iliohypogastric nerve originates from the L1 nerve root."],"references":["Howard, R., Kullmann, D., Werring, D., \u0026 Zandi, M. (Eds.). (2024). Neurology: a queen square textbook. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Science","Matejc\u00edk V. Anatomical variations of lumbosacral plexus. Surg Radiol Anat. 2010 Apr;32(4):409-14. doi: 10.1007/s00276-009-0546-3. Epub 2009 Aug 21. PMID: 19696958."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64098"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17305"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64098"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T16:20:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T16:21:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9995"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78750"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u